We can't travel to the stars yet but the very real possibility of visiting them through a telescope exists. There is no theoretical limit to the size of a reflector dish. A curved mirror that looks similar to a radio telescope but gathers light in a similar way to an optical telescope.<br>
So why don't we just build a 100 kilometre wide parabolic mirror and take a look at the tops of Alien heads going about their business on some strange planet light years away? Because there are limits on construction down here on Earth. We have the technology certainly but the environment is not suitable. Gravity makes it necessary to use superlight materials. That puts an enormous limitation on size. On top of that are temperature variations which distort the very thin material and atmospheric haze. Kind of like looking up through a pond and requiring complex computer programming to correct. Lastly, even if you want to put it into space like Hubble you have the added stress of launching it. As if contending with 1 gravity isn't bad enough you now have to make your mirror capable of withstanding several G's.<br>
<br>
What's the answer?<br>
<br>
Build it in space.<br>
<br>
Zero gravity would make it easier to construct more perfect dishes and coat them with a reflective finish. It would allow us to build telescopes to any size we want, depending on the degree of industrial infrastructure we have off Earth. That infrastructure ofcourse being dependant on our current launch methods. Using nuclear power we could easily set up facilities straight away.<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://a52.g.akamaitech.net/f/52/827/1d/www.space.com/images/h_in_extrasolar_painting_03,0.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
In zero gravity conditions liquids naturally form into perfect spheres or bubbles. Far more perfect than anything we could ever hope to make on Earth. Already there is talk of using this property of space to produce ballbearings of a superior quality. It's time to think bigger. With telescopes big enough to map the solar systems neighbouring us we can better understand the science of planetary formation. That will help us realise our own position in the universe. Whether our own solar system is typical or rare and if other Earths exist in our region of the Galaxy. It would be a magnifying glass we could point in any direction and use to scrutinise the planets of other stars.<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://a52.g.akamaitech.net/f/52/827/1d/www.space.com/images/h_planet_confusion_01,1.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
We are but a small rock orbiting one of a hundred billion Suns in a Galaxy surrounded by other Galaxies just as numerous. The Universe is indescribably huge and we haven't really started exploring it. Not even by telescope. The only extrasolar planets identified to date dwarf Jupiter in size. They are closer to being small unignited stars than Worlds.    <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
